goals.question: What is the distribution of population across zip codes?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the spread of population across different zip codes and identify any outliers.

goals.question: What is the average income of households in each zip code?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of average income by zip code
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify the zip codes with higher average income and understand the income distribution across different zip codes.

goals.question: What is the relationship between population and number of businesses in each zip code?

goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is any correlation between population and number of businesses in each zip code.

goals.question: What is the distribution of land area across zip codes?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the spread of land area across different zip codes and identify any outliers.

goals.question: What is the racial diversity in each zip code?
goals.visualization: Stacked bar chart of racial distribution by zip code
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the racial diversity in each zip code and identify any patterns or outliers.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.hist(data['population'], bins=50, color='blue')
    plt.axvline(data['population'].mean(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label='Mean')
    plt.axvline(data['population'].median(), color='green', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label='Median')
    plt.xlabel('Population')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('What is the distribution of population across zip codes?', wrap=True)
    return plt

data = pd.read_csv('zipcodes.csv')
chart = plot(data)
```

```
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['AVG_INCOME'] = data['AVG_INCOME'].astype(float)
    data = data.groupby('ZIPCODE').mean().reset_index()
    data = data.sort_values(by='AVG_INCOME', ascending=False)
    plt.bar(data['ZIPCODE'], data['AVG_INCOME'], color='blue')
    plt.axhline(y=data['AVG_INCOME'].mean(), color='red', linestyle='--', label='Average Income')
    plt.xlabel('Zip Code')
    plt.ylabel('Average Income')
    plt.title('What is the average income of households in each zip code?')
    plt.legend()
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.scatter(data['population'], data['num_businesses'], alpha=0.5, color='blue')
    plt.xlabel('Population')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Businesses')
    plt.title('What is the relationship between population and number of businesses in each zip code?')
    return plt

data = pd.read_csv('zipcodes.csv')
chart = plot(data)
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data = data.groupby('zip')['white', 'black', 'hispanic', 'asian', 'other'].sum().reset_index()
    data.set_index('zip', inplace=True)
    data.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(15, 10))
    plt.title('What is the racial diversity in each zip code?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Zip Code')
    plt.ylabel('Population')
    plt.legend(loc='upper right')
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```
